WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.100 --> 00:00:04.060
All right. Welcome, everyone. This is the Combating T

2
00:00:04.100 --> 00:00:07.580
Cell Checkpoints Mini Symposium. Thanks for coming.

3
00:00:07.880 --> 00:00:11.680
I'm Megan Berger. I'm an assistant professor at Oregon Health &amp; Science University

4
00:00:11.720 --> 00:00:15.600
in Portland, Oregon, and I'm happy to co-chair this session with Dr.

5
00:00:15.840 --> 00:00:19.480
Justin Klein, who is a professor of medicine at University of Chicago.

6
00:00:20.700 --> 00:00:24.580
So we are both T cell biologists and interested in developing

7
00:00:24.620 --> 00:00:27.680
improved T cell-mediated immunotherapies for cancer.

8
00:00:27.740 --> 00:00:31.620
And so it's great to have the opportunity to organize and

9
00:00:31.780 --> 00:00:35.540
chair this session on just new approaches

10
00:00:35.620 --> 00:00:39.540
to improving T cell function against cancer to try

11
00:00:39.580 --> 00:00:42.740
to further improve patient outcomes.

12
00:00:42.820 --> 00:00:46.790
So we know immune checkpoint inhibitors have made a real impact in

13
00:00:46.800 --> 00:00:50.720
the clinic for many patients. These are things such as anti-PD-1.

14
00:00:51.620 --> 00:00:55.440
However, for many patients, these therapies are not sufficient to

15
00:00:55.520 --> 00:00:58.960
overcome T cell dysfunction in the tumor microenvironment.

16
00:00:58.980 --> 00:01:02.360
And so this session is really focused on some interesting new

17
00:01:02.400 --> 00:01:05.660
approaches to improve T cell function against cancer.

18
00:01:05.700 --> 00:01:08.820
And we're going to cover things from improving T cell

19
00:01:08.860 --> 00:01:09.810
metabolism,

20
00:01:10.640 --> 00:01:14.460
to bolstering cytotoxic function, and also

21
00:01:14.500 --> 00:01:16.180
preventing T cell exhaustion.

22
00:01:17.140 --> 00:01:20.920
So these are really interesting mechanistic talks, and these

23
00:01:20.940 --> 00:01:24.920
mechanisms could be applied, targeting in combination

24
00:01:24.960 --> 00:01:28.580
with checkpoint blockade immunotherapy to bolster endogenous T cell

25
00:01:28.620 --> 00:01:29.760
responses.

26
00:01:30.620 --> 00:01:34.320
The speakers are also looking at these in the context of engineering adoptive T

27
00:01:34.460 --> 00:01:37.160
cell transfer for ACT therapies as well.

28
00:01:38.020 --> 00:01:41.780
So thank you to the speakers for sharing these new insights with us.

29
00:01:42.000 --> 00:01:45.580
And we're actually going to start off with two talks that are focused on improving

30
00:01:45.620 --> 00:01:47.980
T cell metabolism and

31
00:01:48.960 --> 00:01:52.440
trying to develop better immunotherapies for

32
00:01:52.580 --> 00:01:56.400
glioblastoma, which is a notoriously hard to treat cancer in the brain.

33
00:01:57.220 --> 00:02:00.920
So with that, I'll just introduce, I don't have names up here,

34
00:02:01.000 --> 00:02:03.040
but Defne.

35
00:02:05.700 --> 00:02:06.580
I should have brought it with me.

36
00:02:08.440 --> 00:02:08.980
Thank you.

37
00:02:11.780 --> 00:02:13.900
Sorry, I'll just introduce Defne Bayik,

38
00:02:14.800 --> 00:02:18.020
who's coming to us from the University of Miami, and she's going to tell us about

39
00:02:18.060 --> 00:02:21.640
DPP4 as a novel checkpoint for CD8 T

40
00:02:21.800 --> 00:02:22.060
cells.

41
00:02:25.560 --> 00:02:26.030
Welcome.

42
00:02:26.300 --> 00:02:30.160
Thank you very much to the session chairs for organizing such an interesting mini

43
00:02:30.180 --> 00:02:33.840
symposium. I am actually a myeloid cell biologist who turned into a T

44
00:02:33.900 --> 00:02:37.820
cell person, not by choice, but that's where the research led

45
00:02:37.860 --> 00:02:41.140
us. So there are no relevant disclosures for this talk.

46
00:02:43.260 --> 00:02:47.240
As the chair highlighted, the first talk is on glioblastoma, or in short

47
00:02:47.300 --> 00:02:50.100
GBM, which is the most common primary malignant brain tumor.

48
00:02:50.860 --> 00:02:54.800
So to underscore the

49
00:02:54.820 --> 00:02:58.760
importance of developing new treatments for this disease, the standard of

50
00:02:58.800 --> 00:03:02.420
care has not changed in the last two decades, but unfortunately, immune

51
00:03:02.430 --> 00:03:06.370
therapy strategies did not lead to measurable clinical outcomes

52
00:03:06.420 --> 00:03:09.920
thus far. So these tumors are characterized by

53
00:03:10.020 --> 00:03:13.700
immune checkpoint resistance and generally low immune therapy

54
00:03:13.710 --> 00:03:17.400
responses. And we can discuss extensively why that is the

55
00:03:17.460 --> 00:03:20.900
case. The localization of the tumor is an important

56
00:03:20.940 --> 00:03:24.520
factor. It's in the brain. It's hard to get therapeutics there.

57
00:03:25.000 --> 00:03:28.940
But also these tumors are excessively infiltrated by

58
00:03:29.000 --> 00:03:31.130
immune suppressive myeloid cell populations.

59
00:03:31.220 --> 00:03:35.160
Different kind of immune populations are present in this tumor microenvironment.

60
00:03:35.650 --> 00:03:38.980
And these patients are generally characterized by low T cell numbers.

61
00:03:39.100 --> 00:03:42.580
This is induced by both the disease itself and the treatment approaches.

62
00:03:43.460 --> 00:03:46.240
However, there is still somewhat T cell infiltration.

63
00:03:46.280 --> 00:03:50.100
The numbers are low, but they are not undetectable, and those T

64
00:03:50.120 --> 00:03:52.960
cells show the characteristics of exhausted T cells.

65
00:03:53.840 --> 00:03:57.520
So likely a strategy that will generate an

66
00:03:57.560 --> 00:04:01.520
anti-tumor immune response for GBM involves multimodal targeting

67
00:04:01.580 --> 00:04:03.880
that would include the myeloid cells and T cells.

68
00:04:04.600 --> 00:04:08.360
So in an effort to understand the drivers of this myeloid cell recruitment

69
00:04:08.520 --> 00:04:12.480
back in 2022, we reported that there

70
00:04:12.540 --> 00:04:15.480
are some molecules that could inform chemotaxis of these cells to the

71
00:04:15.540 --> 00:04:19.360
microenvironment. So looking at the epigenetic architecture of these

72
00:04:19.380 --> 00:04:22.840
cells, we identified dipeptidyl

73
00:04:22.860 --> 00:04:26.780
peptidase-4, or in short DPP4, as a potential driver

74
00:04:26.900 --> 00:04:30.640
of monastic recruitment to the tumor microenvironment.

75
00:04:30.780 --> 00:04:33.400
But what is this molecule and why it could be important?

76
00:04:34.320 --> 00:04:37.840
So DPP4 is actually understudied, but a very well

77
00:04:37.880 --> 00:04:39.159
drug target.

78
00:04:39.960 --> 00:04:43.820
It's an exopeptidase that is membrane-bound or can be cleaved and released

79
00:04:43.860 --> 00:04:47.080
into plasma, and its best described function is its

80
00:04:47.120 --> 00:04:50.620
exopeptidase activity. It primarily targets

81
00:04:50.680 --> 00:04:54.260
GLP-1, so it has a critical role in insulin glucose metabolism.

82
00:04:54.700 --> 00:04:58.500
However, it is not specific. There are multiple cytokine and chemokine targets,

83
00:04:59.360 --> 00:05:03.340
and their cleavage could affect bioactivity and bioavailability,

84
00:05:03.460 --> 00:05:06.900
but we really don't have a good understanding of how it modulates

85
00:05:06.980 --> 00:05:08.180
cytokines, chemokines.

86
00:05:09.200 --> 00:05:11.520
Also, I mentioned that it's a membrane-bound protein.

87
00:05:11.720 --> 00:05:15.640
It interacts with other proteins that are on the membrane, and therefore it has a

88
00:05:15.700 --> 00:05:17.560
signaling function, which is even

89
00:05:19.260 --> 00:05:20.000
worse described.

90
00:05:20.830 --> 00:05:24.750
But because it is so critical for insulin glucose metabolism, it's very well

91
00:05:24.800 --> 00:05:28.620
drug. So gliptins target DPP4, and there are six

92
00:05:28.660 --> 00:05:32.560
approved inhibitors against these molecules, sitagliptin being the one that is

93
00:05:32.640 --> 00:05:33.490
used most commonly.

94
00:05:34.320 --> 00:05:37.140
So having identified DPP4 as a potential

95
00:05:38.280 --> 00:05:42.180
molecule that is important for immune suppressive myeloid cell activity, we asked

96
00:05:42.200 --> 00:05:45.780
the question: Are the inhibitors effective in patients with

97
00:05:45.800 --> 00:05:46.580
glioblastoma?

98
00:05:47.500 --> 00:05:50.950
So we turned into the Medicare data set and performed a retrospective

99
00:05:51.020 --> 00:05:54.220
analysis where we looked for the patients who were on DPP4

100
00:05:54.260 --> 00:05:58.080
inhibitors. So here the pink line

101
00:05:58.140 --> 00:05:59.280
highlights standard of care.

102
00:06:00.300 --> 00:06:04.180
When we look at the patients who happen to be on gliptins,

103
00:06:04.260 --> 00:06:07.840
DPP4 inhibitors, we observed that they were having much better outcomes

104
00:06:07.940 --> 00:06:11.696
compared to patients who received standard of care.Presumably, these

105
00:06:11.716 --> 00:06:14.156
patients are using this drug because they are diabetic.

106
00:06:14.576 --> 00:06:18.426
So we use metformin as a drug control, and we observed that it didn't

107
00:06:18.496 --> 00:06:22.376
have the same survival benefit that is conferred by inhibition of DPP4.

108
00:06:23.596 --> 00:06:26.416
So the question is that, what is the main target of DPP4?

109
00:06:26.456 --> 00:06:29.776
Yes, it is expressed by myeloids cells, but is it the end of story?

110
00:06:30.576 --> 00:06:34.356
We looked at multiple single cell sequencing data sets and we observed that

111
00:06:34.396 --> 00:06:38.036
CD8 T cells are characterized by profoundly high levels of

112
00:06:38.076 --> 00:06:41.976
DPP4 expression. And we can recapitulate this on

113
00:06:42.316 --> 00:06:46.196
our orthotopic GPR models, where we observe CD8

114
00:06:46.676 --> 00:06:48.936
T cells were the main expressers of DPP4.

115
00:06:49.636 --> 00:06:53.316
And in fact, they were critical for DPP4 inhibitor response.

116
00:06:53.396 --> 00:06:55.956
So this is a very immune system persistent model.

117
00:06:56.436 --> 00:07:00.176
When we treated these mice with tumors with sitagliptin,

118
00:07:00.576 --> 00:07:04.496
there was a survival benefit, which was totally reversed by inhibition

119
00:07:04.536 --> 00:07:05.596
of CD8 T cells.

120
00:07:06.476 --> 00:07:08.656
So what kind of CD8 T cells express that?

121
00:07:08.836 --> 00:07:12.116
And we did multiple analysis to answer this question.

122
00:07:12.496 --> 00:07:16.296
Initially, we looked at patient samples, and all the cells are exhausted, to

123
00:07:16.336 --> 00:07:20.246
remind you, but we separated based on tox expression, and we observed

124
00:07:20.246 --> 00:07:23.546
that these cells with higher tox expression, presumably these are the terminally

125
00:07:23.576 --> 00:07:26.895
exhausted T cells, had higher levels of DPP4 expression.

126
00:07:27.876 --> 00:07:29.256
We also used an acute and

127
00:07:30.116 --> 00:07:33.486
chronic LC-MS model to study T cell biology more effectively.

128
00:07:34.276 --> 00:07:38.056
Initially, what we observed was naive T cells have high DPP4 expression, but

129
00:07:38.136 --> 00:07:42.116
when they get activated, the expression levels go down, only

130
00:07:42.156 --> 00:07:45.436
to go back up with exhaustion or memory differentiation.

131
00:07:47.056 --> 00:07:50.896
If we again use an orthogonal assay and use a chronic antigen stimulation assay, we

132
00:07:50.976 --> 00:07:54.456
observed that terminally exhausted T cells have much higher levels of

133
00:07:54.496 --> 00:07:57.016
DPP4 expression compared to effector subset.

134
00:07:57.856 --> 00:08:01.136
So this suggests that there is some lineage

135
00:08:01.216 --> 00:08:04.916
activation relationship between DPP4 expression.

136
00:08:06.376 --> 00:08:10.296
But it doesn't necessarily say that the DPP4 is

137
00:08:10.336 --> 00:08:10.856
functional.

138
00:08:11.736 --> 00:08:15.416
To understand better whether it has a functional role, we again pharmacologically

139
00:08:15.456 --> 00:08:18.336
inhibited on T cells and performed an RNA sequencing

140
00:08:18.396 --> 00:08:22.096
experiment. So overall, there were two

141
00:08:22.116 --> 00:08:26.086
clusters of pathway that were upregulated upon inhibition of DPP4

142
00:08:26.116 --> 00:08:29.966
in T cells, one being T cell activation related pathways,

143
00:08:30.296 --> 00:08:33.076
the other being mitochondrial metabolism related pathways.

144
00:08:34.096 --> 00:08:37.656
To functionally confirm that, we can do proliferation assay, and we

145
00:08:37.716 --> 00:08:41.516
observed that both in human and mouse, the inhibition of

146
00:08:41.536 --> 00:08:44.216
DPP4 increases proliferation rates.

147
00:08:44.876 --> 00:08:46.586
We observed that these T cells,

148
00:08:47.716 --> 00:08:51.336
that are treated with sitagliptin are generating more cytotoxic mediators.

149
00:08:51.956 --> 00:08:55.076
We also observed that they were better at killing cancer targets in an

150
00:08:55.116 --> 00:08:56.276
antigen-specific manner.

151
00:08:57.956 --> 00:09:01.916
What about the metabolism? So we have a growing appreciation for dynamic regulation

152
00:09:01.956 --> 00:09:04.496
of T cell metabolism and how it relates to function.

153
00:09:06.036 --> 00:09:09.886
At the basal state, they have lower metabolic activity, but when T cells get

154
00:09:09.896 --> 00:09:13.816
activated, they first increase glycolysis rate, which is accompanied by

155
00:09:13.836 --> 00:09:17.576
proliferation. And at the effector stage, they do use oxidative

156
00:09:17.596 --> 00:09:20.556
phosphorylation for killing function.

157
00:09:21.276 --> 00:09:25.236
And when they differentiate into memory cells or get exhausted, their metabolism

158
00:09:25.316 --> 00:09:26.956
again goes through another round of change.

159
00:09:28.076 --> 00:09:28.256
So

160
00:09:29.436 --> 00:09:33.316
based on this, we did a targeted metabolomic analysis and what

161
00:09:33.336 --> 00:09:36.756
we observed was there was a significant upregulation of metabolites that are

162
00:09:36.816 --> 00:09:40.516
associated with nucleotide and amino acid metabolisms, which matches

163
00:09:40.676 --> 00:09:42.996
our observation that these cells are proliferating.

164
00:09:43.776 --> 00:09:47.016
We also observed that both TCA cycle-related metabolites and

165
00:09:47.076 --> 00:09:49.936
glycolysis-related metabolites were getting upregulated.

166
00:09:51.856 --> 00:09:55.036
So is that really the case? We can look at that by

167
00:09:55.996 --> 00:09:59.956
measuring oxidative phosphorylation rate and glycolysis and looking

168
00:09:59.976 --> 00:10:03.916
at oxidative phosphorylation. We observed an

169
00:10:03.976 --> 00:10:07.716
increase in spare mitochondrial respiratory capacity, and we

170
00:10:07.796 --> 00:10:11.496
also observed increased glycolysis rates, suggesting that T cells were becoming

171
00:10:11.576 --> 00:10:14.516
more metabolically fit when we inhibit the DPP4.

172
00:10:16.216 --> 00:10:20.196
What about the mechanism? I mentioned to you that DPP4 is mostly described as

173
00:10:20.216 --> 00:10:22.736
an exo peptidase, but it does have a signaling function.

174
00:10:22.816 --> 00:10:24.976
So what could these signaling partners could be?

175
00:10:25.856 --> 00:10:29.596
To address that, we did a phosphoproteomics analysis, and we observed

176
00:10:30.036 --> 00:10:33.276
upregulation in T cell receptor signaling mediators.

177
00:10:33.816 --> 00:10:37.356
But our top target, unexpectedly, was an enzyme called

178
00:10:37.456 --> 00:10:40.736
glutamate carboxylase 1, or GAD1 in short.

179
00:10:41.996 --> 00:10:45.696
So GAD1 is an important metabolic enzyme that converts

180
00:10:45.756 --> 00:10:49.676
glutamate into GABA and then feeds it into TCA cycle.

181
00:10:49.716 --> 00:10:53.676
So it matches our observation that TCA cycle is getting upregulated.

182
00:10:54.556 --> 00:10:57.496
So does this enzyme really play a role in T cell

183
00:10:57.536 --> 00:11:00.516
functionality and DPP4 inhibitor response?

184
00:11:01.616 --> 00:11:05.536
Lucky for us, this is an enzyme that is inhibited in the context

185
00:11:05.576 --> 00:11:09.256
of neuroscience. So there is an inhibitor called L-glycine that we can

186
00:11:10.056 --> 00:11:11.886
test its functional role.

187
00:11:12.756 --> 00:11:14.296
So in both mouse

188
00:11:15.176 --> 00:11:19.156
and human T cells, what we observed was that inhibition of DPP4 with

189
00:11:19.216 --> 00:11:23.056
sitagliptin led to an increase in spare respiratory capacity,

190
00:11:23.516 --> 00:11:26.276
which was mitigated by inhibition of GAD1.

191
00:11:28.196 --> 00:11:31.756
Also, we observed that the proliferative advantage conferred by

192
00:11:31.796 --> 00:11:35.756
DPP4 inhibition was blocked when we

193
00:11:35.936 --> 00:11:37.556
inhibited GAD1.

194
00:11:38.796 --> 00:11:42.736
So this really identifies GAD1 as a downstream modulator of T cell

195
00:11:42.816 --> 00:11:43.516
biology.

196
00:11:44.696 --> 00:11:48.246
But more important, what is the functional importance of this observation?

197
00:11:48.376 --> 00:11:52.236
Can we repurpose this clinically used DPP4 inhibitors

198
00:11:52.246 --> 00:11:54.826
for treatment, and can we combine with immune therapies?

199
00:11:55.876 --> 00:11:59.156
So one thing that is important was for us to

200
00:11:59.216 --> 00:12:00.456
identify whether

201
00:12:01.296 --> 00:12:03.456
CAR T cells have the same kind of response.

202
00:12:03.896 --> 00:12:07.856
And here I'm showing you mouse B7-H3 CAR T cells, but

203
00:12:07.896 --> 00:12:11.776
we do have similar results with human IL-13 receptor alpha 2 and CD19

204
00:12:11.816 --> 00:12:15.492
CAR T cells.So in this experiment, what we did was a chronic

205
00:12:15.512 --> 00:12:17.552
stimulation, repeated stimulation experiment.

206
00:12:18.252 --> 00:12:21.762
So vehicle-treated CAR T cells, beyond stimulation three, lose their

207
00:12:22.012 --> 00:12:25.132
efficacy, and they no longer lyse tumor targets effectively.

208
00:12:25.812 --> 00:12:29.392
But what we observed with the dapagliflozin-treated CAR Ts were that they retained

209
00:12:29.402 --> 00:12:32.412
their functional activity to up to eight stimulation.

210
00:12:33.452 --> 00:12:37.192
And in fact, when we treat these CAR Ts during the manufacturing

211
00:12:37.272 --> 00:12:40.712
process and then transfer them into

212
00:12:41.492 --> 00:12:45.392
mouse models with pediatric gliomas, we observed we achieved a better

213
00:12:45.412 --> 00:12:49.372
tumor control, suggesting that these CAR T cells were more therapeutically active.

214
00:12:50.512 --> 00:12:54.492
So all in all, what I shared with you today suggests that DPP4 could

215
00:12:54.952 --> 00:12:58.912
serve as a immunometabolic checkpoint where the expression level is informed

216
00:12:58.952 --> 00:13:02.752
by T cell activation state. And when we repurpose a Type 2

217
00:13:02.792 --> 00:13:06.352
diabetes drug, we can reinvigorate T cell

218
00:13:06.392 --> 00:13:09.412
metabolism and increase functional activity for anti-tumor

219
00:13:11.112 --> 00:13:12.412
function.

220
00:13:13.332 --> 00:13:14.952
So with that, I would like to thank Dr.

221
00:13:15.172 --> 00:13:19.012
Oriana Taran-Pumar, who is the postdoc who led this project, along with all

222
00:13:19.092 --> 00:13:23.052
the collaborators, and happy to answer any questions you have. Thank you.

223
00:13:30.952 --> 00:13:32.932
Just come up to the microphone if you have questions.

224
00:13:34.792 --> 00:13:35.892
So I'll start with one.

225
00:13:37.352 --> 00:13:40.932
So your studies all used the inhibitor of

226
00:13:40.972 --> 00:13:44.812
DPP4, yeah? I'm just curious how specific of an inhibitor

227
00:13:44.832 --> 00:13:48.312
that is and whether you looked at genetic or conditional targeting of

228
00:13:48.352 --> 00:13:48.952
DPP4.

229
00:13:49.432 --> 00:13:51.952
We did use global knockout mice, DPP4.

230
00:13:52.012 --> 00:13:55.792
We didn't use conditional, but global knockout mice have the same effect.

231
00:13:55.912 --> 00:13:59.612
We also treated T cells that are obtained from DPP4 knockout mice and

232
00:13:59.652 --> 00:14:03.412
treated them with the drug to confirm specificity, and we

233
00:14:03.932 --> 00:14:06.332
believe that the effect is specific for the most part.

234
00:14:06.612 --> 00:14:10.452
I know that there is potential of target effect on DPP7,

235
00:14:10.512 --> 00:14:11.432
DPP8, other

236
00:14:12.632 --> 00:14:16.162
DPP family molecules. But in knockout mice, we

237
00:14:16.392 --> 00:14:18.152
see that the response is

238
00:14:19.112 --> 00:14:21.032
diminishing, the drug response.

239
00:14:21.332 --> 00:14:21.671
Thank you.

240
00:14:21.812 --> 00:14:22.592
Pretty specific.

241
00:14:24.292 --> 00:14:25.172
Great talk. Thank you.

242
00:14:25.992 --> 00:14:26.712
Two questions.

243
00:14:28.152 --> 00:14:31.572
What about the effect on the myeloid component of these tumors?

244
00:14:33.492 --> 00:14:36.772
Yes. So it does affect

245
00:14:36.852 --> 00:14:40.112
chemotaxis, but it doesn't seem to affect functionality.

246
00:14:40.212 --> 00:14:43.992
So it looks like they have different biological outcomes on different cell

247
00:14:44.032 --> 00:14:47.972
types specific, and that's one of the reasons why we went into CAR T

