00:46:10.420 --> 00:46:13.140
beneficial for this particular response.

792
00:46:13.840 --> 00:46:14.120
But

793
00:46:15.120 --> 00:46:18.120
it's possible that we're just unlocking

794
00:46:18.200 --> 00:46:22.180
some curious new biology in the absence of A20

795
00:46:22.220 --> 00:46:25.480
that somehow connects to this really highly

796
00:46:25.520 --> 00:46:28.080
regulated step of degranulation.

797
00:46:28.120 --> 00:46:28.640
But yeah, we

798
00:46:29.480 --> 00:46:32.890
don't fully know. We know that it's not related to

799
00:46:32.960 --> 00:46:36.340
IL1. We've done those knockout

800
00:46:36.380 --> 00:46:40.120
experiments. We're still working on gasdermin D, but

801
00:46:40.160 --> 00:46:42.860
again, that's a cell death related thing too.

802
00:46:42.980 --> 00:46:43.880
So

803
00:46:45.260 --> 00:46:48.780
it might end up requiring more high level proteomics to figure out.

804
00:46:49.440 --> 00:46:51.280
But yeah, we don't fully know right now.

805
00:46:52.000 --> 00:46:52.520
Thank you.

806
00:46:52.600 --> 00:46:52.819
Mm-hmm.

807
00:46:55.400 --> 00:46:57.700
Great talk. This is Rob Manguso from MGH.

808
00:46:59.420 --> 00:47:02.580
You mentioned that as part of your future directions, that you're looking at

809
00:47:02.620 --> 00:47:06.140
upstream signaling, but because this can function

