00:48:44.658 --> 00:48:45.208
Thank you.

843
00:48:45.238 --> 00:48:48.928
But yeah, we get all the traditional, the expected

844
00:48:49.028 --> 00:48:52.368
NF-?B upregulation as well.

845
00:48:52.748 --> 00:48:53.648
Cool. Great talk.

846
00:48:56.748 --> 00:48:58.668
All right. Thank you very much. Great talk.

847
00:49:03.728 --> 00:49:07.368
All right. Next up is Marco Scheidegger, a graduate

848
00:49:07.408 --> 00:49:09.768
student who comes to us from Buenos Aires.

849
00:49:10.888 --> 00:49:14.628
He's going to talk to us about galectin-1 and exhausted CD8 T cells.

850
00:49:17.988 --> 00:49:19.808
Hi. Thank you for the introduction.

851
00:49:20.808 --> 00:49:24.508
Yeah, as you said, this is part of my ongoing PhD project.

852
00:49:24.608 --> 00:49:27.128
I am currently in Buenos Aires in Argentina.

853
00:49:28.588 --> 00:49:32.168
Mostly in our group, we focus on galectin-1, which I'm going to introduce in a bit.

854
00:49:32.768 --> 00:49:36.548
And my project in particular focuses on how galectin-1

855
00:49:36.608 --> 00:49:36.828
can

856
00:49:37.768 --> 00:49:41.128
regulate this CD8 T cell dysfunction and exhaustion.

857
00:49:41.748 --> 00:49:44.408
So these are my disclosure information.

858
00:49:45.068 --> 00:49:48.578
And I thought I could start this talk not actually revisiting the whole cancer

859
00:49:48.628 --> 00:49:52.428
immunity cycle. I'm sure you've heard it enough in this congress

860
00:49:52.488 --> 00:49:56.108
so far, but rather by talking about what happens when T cells actually

861
00:49:56.168 --> 00:49:59.768
reach the tumor site. And basically what happens is that they will

862
00:49:59.808 --> 00:50:03.728
encounter a rather complex tumor microenvironment where there's

863
00:50:03.788 --> 00:50:06.928
a balance or an imbalance, actually,

864
00:50:07.908 --> 00:50:11.758
consisting of activating signals which would favor the anti-tumor response,

865
00:50:11.828 --> 00:50:15.308
but mostly they will find a lot of immunosuppressive signals.

866
00:50:15.348 --> 00:50:19.028
So there's a lot of activation of their co-inhibitory receptors, there's a lot of

867
00:50:19.068 --> 00:50:21.228
different immunosuppressive myeloid populations.

868
00:50:21.928 --> 00:50:25.808
And this imbalance in the tumor will eventually lead

869
00:50:25.868 --> 00:50:29.288
up to what we call the CD8 dysfunction or exhaustion.

870
00:50:30.088 --> 00:50:33.218
It's important to note that when we're talking about exhaustion, we're not talking

871
00:50:33.268 --> 00:50:37.108
about just one specific phenotypic state in

872
00:50:37.168 --> 00:50:40.728
CD8 T cells, but we're talking about a whole differentiation pathway.

873
00:50:40.788 --> 00:50:43.628
So basically what happens is that because of repeated or

874
00:50:44.588 --> 00:50:48.388
of chronic antigen stimulation, cells will progress in this

875
00:50:48.408 --> 00:50:52.368
path going through what we call the progenitor exhausted T cells, winding up

876
00:50:52.447 --> 00:50:54.148
in the terminally exhausted T cells.

877
00:50:54.828 --> 00:50:57.928
And along this path, they will lose effector functions.

878
00:50:57.968 --> 00:51:00.088
They will gain what we call a dysfunctional phenotype

879
00:51:00.908 --> 00:51:04.168
coupled with increased co-inhibitory receptor expression,

880
00:51:06.088 --> 00:51:09.968
loss of polyfunctional cytokines, and a lot of different

881
00:51:10.008 --> 00:51:11.868
epigenetic and transcriptomic changes.

882
00:51:13.468 --> 00:51:17.148
And while we do know a lot about how this program is carried out,

883
00:51:17.508 --> 00:51:21.478
mainly chronic antigen stimulation being the driver, there are a

884
00:51:21.508 --> 00:51:22.268
lot of different

885
00:51:24.488 --> 00:51:28.148
soluble molecules in the microenvironment which could not drive this process, but

886
00:51:28.168 --> 00:51:32.008
regulate this process, how far or how easy or how fast

887
00:51:32.088 --> 00:51:36.028
can this process go. And one of these molecules is what we are focusing

888
00:51:36.068 --> 00:51:37.668
on in our lab, which is galectin-1.

889
00:51:38.168 --> 00:51:42.108
Galectin-1 is a glycan binding protein which in our lab we have studied

890
00:51:42.148 --> 00:51:45.828
for the past 20 years. It has both intracellular and

891
00:51:45.888 --> 00:51:49.237
extracellular functions, and it is highly expressed by

892
00:51:49.768 --> 00:51:50.448
most tumors.

893
00:51:52.228 --> 00:51:55.588
Along all the functions that we know of, mostly related to the immune

894
00:51:55.808 --> 00:51:59.068
compartments, we know, for example, that galectin-1 promotes the

895
00:51:59.368 --> 00:52:02.848
polarization of dendritic cells towards immunosuppressive

896
00:52:02.888 --> 00:52:06.428
phenotype. We know it polarizes macrophages towards an M2-like

897
00:52:06.448 --> 00:52:06.978
phenotype.

898
00:52:08.028 --> 00:52:11.108
Regarding angiogenesis, we know that galectin-1 also favors

899
00:52:11.488 --> 00:52:13.928
angiogenesis even during anti-VEGF blockade.

900
00:52:14.528 --> 00:52:18.478
We know it favors the selective deletion of T helper 1 and

901
00:52:18.488 --> 00:52:21.508
T helper 17 cells. We also know that it

902
00:52:22.288 --> 00:52:25.028
expands Treg cells in tumor microenvironment.

903
00:52:25.348 --> 00:52:28.677
And most recently, we found that it triggers immunosuppressive and

904
00:52:28.728 --> 00:52:32.048
proangiogenic programs through what we call the myeloid-derived suppressor cells.

905
00:52:33.148 --> 00:52:36.608
However, in all these years, we have always focused on galectin-1

906
00:52:37.408 --> 00:52:41.308
derived from the tumor. So we know that most tumors produce galectin-1, and

907
00:52:41.368 --> 00:52:41.968
we all

908
00:52:43.588 --> 00:52:46.488
went rather deep with the functions of this tumor-derived galectin-1.

909
00:52:46.988 --> 00:52:50.588
But for this work, we wanted to switch up the focus a bit and focus on what we call

910
00:52:50.628 --> 00:52:50.748
the

911
00:52:51.628 --> 00:52:54.908
host-derived galectin-1. We know host cells also produce

912
00:52:55.108 --> 00:52:58.888
galectin-1. They can secrete it as well, and also immune cells can secrete

913
00:52:58.928 --> 00:53:02.588
galectin-1. So in this case, we wanted to focus on immune cell-derived

914
00:53:02.648 --> 00:53:06.068
Gal-1, and particularly what happens on T cells, which are the main

915
00:53:06.308 --> 00:53:08.828
effectors of the anti-tumor response.

916
00:53:08.868 --> 00:53:12.628
As a first approach, what we did was we analyzed publicly available single cell

917
00:53:12.748 --> 00:53:16.488
RNA-seq data, and we found that as cells progress towards more exhausted

918
00:53:16.568 --> 00:53:19.888
phenotypes, they will start secreting or expressing

919
00:53:19.908 --> 00:53:21.808
actually more and more galectin-1.

920
00:53:22.788 --> 00:53:26.628
And this coupled with our own in vivo studies, what we did was we first analyzed

921
00:53:27.108 --> 00:53:30.528
a vaccination model. We vaccinated wild type and knockout mice with

922
00:53:30.828 --> 00:53:32.888
B16-OVA tumors. And

923
00:53:33.788 --> 00:53:37.728
while we did not see an improved control when we deleted, when

924
00:53:37.768 --> 00:53:41.708
the mice lacked galectin-1 actually, when we analyzed at endpoint

925
00:53:41.748 --> 00:53:45.608
the infiltrate of these tumors and we analyzed the T cell population, we

926
00:53:45.688 --> 00:53:47.448
see that they are expressing less of this

927
00:53:48.568 --> 00:53:51.088
exhaustion associated transcription factor, which is Tox.

928
00:53:51.568 --> 00:53:53.508
So this led us to ask ourselves if

929
00:53:54.688 --> 00:53:58.588
galectin-1 and exhaustion are not just a correlation, but maybe a

930
00:53:58.628 --> 00:54:02.468
causation. So our main question in this work was does

931
00:54:02.528 --> 00:54:06.118
endogenous galectin-1 or T cell-derived galectin-1 shape this

932
00:54:06.488 --> 00:54:08.028
T cell exhaustion and dysfunction?

933
00:54:08.808 --> 00:54:12.628
As a first approach, what we did, what we turned to in vitro models of exhaustion,

934
00:54:13.048 --> 00:54:16.578
we simulate what happens on the cancer immunity cycle, basically by

935
00:54:16.888 --> 00:54:19.308
repeating antigen stimulation on T cells.

936
00:54:19.688 --> 00:54:23.128
So we activate them, we let them rest for a few days, and then we reactivate them.

937
00:54:23.768 --> 00:54:27.398
And the first thing we did was we validated our

938
00:54:27.448 --> 00:54:31.168
results or the public results from the single cell RNA-seq,

939
00:54:31.548 --> 00:54:35.318
and we verified that upon chronic stimulation of T cells

940
00:54:35.768 --> 00:54:37.788
they are expressing more and more galectin-1.

941
00:54:38.628 --> 00:54:41.008
And then comparing wild type or knockout cells

942
00:54:41.808 --> 00:54:43.028
first we validated the model.

943
00:54:44.208 --> 00:54:48.128
We analyzed by flow cytometry expression of PD-1, and we see that after

944
00:54:48.148 --> 00:54:51.668
the second reactivation, they express higher levels of PD-1, which will

945
00:54:51.988 --> 00:54:55.932
validate that these cells are actually going through this exhaustion pathway.And

946
00:54:55.952 --> 00:54:58.912
then when we analyzed TIM-3 expression, which is associated with terminal

947
00:54:58.972 --> 00:55:02.712
exhaustion, we were surprised to see that knockout cells actually express more

948
00:55:03.392 --> 00:55:06.292
TIM-3, so they would seem to be more exhausted.

949
00:55:06.712 --> 00:55:10.152
However, it's important to know that when we're talking about exhaustion, there's

950
00:55:10.192 --> 00:55:13.552
not just one single marker that defines whether a cell is

951
00:55:13.792 --> 00:55:16.212
terminally or progenitorly exhausted.

952
00:55:16.732 --> 00:55:18.852
So we turned to see what happens with the

953
00:55:19.892 --> 00:55:21.532
master regulators of transcription.

954
00:55:21.642 --> 00:55:25.082
And we went to see two of the main transcription factors associated with this

955
00:55:25.082 --> 00:55:27.862
process. So TCF7 is associated with

956
00:55:28.352 --> 00:55:32.302
stem-like phenotype, and TOX is a master regulator of

957
00:55:32.332 --> 00:55:35.132
telomere differentiation in CD8 T cells.

958
00:55:35.592 --> 00:55:39.072
And the first thing we see when we analyze the wild type cells is

959
00:55:39.132 --> 00:55:43.012
that upon this reactivation, they are losing expression of

960
00:55:43.052 --> 00:55:46.582
TCF7, so they are losing this stem-like phenotype, and they are gaining

961
00:55:46.582 --> 00:55:50.372
expression of the terminally exhausted transcription

962
00:55:50.452 --> 00:55:53.852
factor, which is TOX. However, when we look at the knockout cells

963
00:55:54.272 --> 00:55:58.052
lacking galectin-1, we do see the same loss of TCF7, but we do

964
00:55:58.112 --> 00:56:00.032
not see any gain of TOX expression.

965
00:56:00.392 --> 00:56:02.672
So they would seem to be less exhausted in this case.

966
00:56:02.702 --> 00:56:06.672
And more importantly, when we analyze the functional phenotype of these cells, we

967
00:56:06.732 --> 00:56:10.272
see that they are more functional, characterized by higher expression of interferon

968
00:56:10.312 --> 00:56:11.332
gamma and TNF alpha.

969
00:56:12.772 --> 00:56:15.912
After this, we wanted to go to mouse in vivo models,

970
00:56:17.272 --> 00:56:20.592
and we chose an antigen-specific model, which is the OT-1 cells.

971
00:56:20.672 --> 00:56:22.371
They are specific for OVA peptides.

972
00:56:23.012 --> 00:56:26.352
And we took these cells and using CRISPR-Cas9, we knocked down

973
00:56:26.372 --> 00:56:29.392
galectin-1. Here's the validation of that knockout.

974
00:56:29.842 --> 00:56:33.472
And we took these cells, and we transferred them into B and T cell deficient

975
00:56:33.532 --> 00:56:37.522
Rag2 knockout mice which were carrying B16 OVA tumors, so

976
00:56:37.522 --> 00:56:41.512
this is melanoma. And we see a trend towards improved control

977
00:56:41.552 --> 00:56:44.952
when the CD8 T cells that we're transferring are knocked out for

978
00:56:45.072 --> 00:56:49.052
galectin-1. And again, when we analyze this infiltrate at endpoint,

979
00:56:49.192 --> 00:56:51.452
we see a more functional phenotype.

980
00:56:51.612 --> 00:56:54.932
So they're expressing more interferon gamma, and they have higher cytotoxic

981
00:56:54.942 --> 00:56:57.492
capacity measured by granzyme B expression.

982
00:56:58.672 --> 00:56:59.252
So this far,

983
00:57:00.252 --> 00:57:03.852
at least, we are convinced that there is some relation with

984
00:57:03.891 --> 00:57:07.532
galectin-1, and it's driving somehow the dysfunction and exhausted

985
00:57:07.572 --> 00:57:11.352
phenotypes in these cells. So we wondered what possible mechanism

986
00:57:11.392 --> 00:57:14.992
could this be happening through. We switched to

987
00:57:15.812 --> 00:57:19.672
other members of the galectin family, and we found, for example, this is

988
00:57:19.712 --> 00:57:23.592
widely known, that galectin-9, for example, can bind to PD-1 and TIM-3.

989
00:57:23.972 --> 00:57:27.872
It can activate these receptors and lead to persistent of exhausted

990
00:57:27.932 --> 00:57:31.832
T cells. We also know that galectin-3 can bind to PD-1 and to LAG-3

991
00:57:31.872 --> 00:57:34.052
and also lead to T cell dysfunction.

992
00:57:34.772 --> 00:57:38.452
They have also several roles in the myeloid compartment.

993
00:57:38.972 --> 00:57:42.212
So we wondered if galectin-1 could be acting in a similar fashion.

994
00:57:42.592 --> 00:57:46.532
So our next question was, does galectin-1 bind to these co-inhibitory

995
00:57:46.592 --> 00:57:49.192
receptors, and then can it activate them?

996
00:57:50.132 --> 00:57:53.652
So as a first approach, what we did was we took a set of co-inhibitory

997
00:57:53.692 --> 00:57:57.572
molecules, mainly PD-1, CTLA4, TIM-3, LAG-3,

998
00:57:58.072 --> 00:58:02.052
TIGIT, and VISTA, and we did a set of studies to see if there was any

999
00:58:02.112 --> 00:58:05.852
binding. And the first thing we did was a lectin blot, where we see that galectin-1

1000
00:58:05.892 --> 00:58:09.872
actually binds to these receptors with different affinities to most of

1001
00:58:09.912 --> 00:58:13.892
the receptors actually. We didn't see any binding to the TIM-3 in this

1002
00:58:13.932 --> 00:58:14.172
case.

1003
00:58:15.272 --> 00:58:18.012
Then we verified this with a different assay, the solid phase assay.

1004
00:58:18.992 --> 00:58:22.212
We again saw galectin-1 binding to the receptors with different affinities.

1005
00:58:22.252 --> 00:58:25.872
And in this case, we also saw that when we put lactose in the mix, we

1006
00:58:25.892 --> 00:58:29.832
abrogated all binding, and this proved that it's a glycan-dependent interaction.

1007
00:58:30.772 --> 00:58:34.132
Then we took two of these receptors, LAG-3 and VISTA, because it's the

1008
00:58:34.212 --> 00:58:36.652
ones we saw the highest binding with.

1009
00:58:37.052 --> 00:58:39.532
We verified with isothermal titration calorimetry.

1010
00:58:40.112 --> 00:58:43.992
And again, we quantified binding of Gal-1 to LAG-3 with a KD of around

1011
00:58:44.032 --> 00:58:47.792
12 or 13 micromolar, and to VISTA with a KD of

1012
00:58:47.872 --> 00:58:49.072
almost 3 micromolar.

1013
00:58:49.892 --> 00:58:53.832
Finally, we did some biolayer interferometry assays with VISTA in

1014
00:58:53.872 --> 00:58:57.712
particular, and we again saw a quite strong binding of galectin-1 to

1015
00:58:57.732 --> 00:59:01.452
this receptor and verified once more that this binding is actually

1016
00:59:01.472 --> 00:59:05.032
glycan-dependent. So this is all the work I wanted to show you today.

1017
00:59:05.152 --> 00:59:08.852
So just as a wrap-up, we can see that galectin-1

1018
00:59:10.152 --> 00:59:14.091
expression increases during T cell exhaustion and that this

1019
00:59:14.172 --> 00:59:16.091
promotes dysfunction. So

1020
00:59:17.312 --> 00:59:18.122
the next thing we're

1021
00:59:19.772 --> 00:59:23.472
planning to develop this work is analyzing what intracellular

1022
00:59:23.592 --> 00:59:26.842
functions of galectin-1 could possibly be involved in this process.

1023
00:59:28.072 --> 00:59:31.692
Next, we saw that endogenous galectin-1 limits the antitumor

1024
00:59:31.712 --> 00:59:34.782
capacity of these cells, and we're wondering if that could possibly be

1025
00:59:36.012 --> 00:59:37.212
a target for new therapies.

1026
00:59:38.292 --> 00:59:41.712
Mainly, can we block Gal-1 in T cells and improve

1027
00:59:41.752 --> 00:59:45.492
adopted cell transfer regimens? And

1028
00:59:45.572 --> 00:59:49.312
finally, we know that galectin-1 binds to a set of these co-inhibitory

1029
00:59:49.372 --> 00:59:51.152
molecules, and we're not just staying there.

1030
00:59:51.212 --> 00:59:53.892
We want to know if this is not only binding but also activation.

1031
00:59:53.972 --> 00:59:57.912
So the first thing we're going to do is analyze functionally if galectin-1 can

1032
00:59:57.992 --> 01:00:01.872
actually activate signaling pathways through these receptors, and if so, if

1033
01:00:01.912 --> 01:00:05.652
this could be a possible mechanism of resistance to immune checkpoint

1034
01:00:05.712 --> 01:00:09.412
blockade therapies. So we hope to be moving forward in this matter.

1035
01:00:10.032 --> 01:00:13.842
And with that, I wanted to thank all my group for their everyday work,

1036
01:00:13.912 --> 01:00:16.812
and thank you all for listening.

1037
01:00:23.212 --> 01:00:25.312
Thanks very much. We have some time for questions.

1038
01:00:26.192 --> 01:00:29.972
I can start with one. I'm interested in sort of the extracellular

1039
01:00:30.032 --> 01:00:33.852
role and the level of galectin-1 on T cells versus other cells in the tumor

1040
01:00:33.892 --> 01:00:37.352
microenvironment. Do you have an idea of sort of comparative levels

1041
01:00:37.492 --> 01:00:41.312
and therefore maybe comparative contribution in binding

1042
01:00:41.332 --> 01:00:43.012
those inhibitory receptors on T cells?

1043
01:00:43.892 --> 01:00:47.732
We haven't actually compared all the immune population,

1044
01:00:48.212 --> 01:00:50.152
how much galectin-1 they produce.

1045
01:00:50.632 --> 01:00:54.552
But we know that in some tumors, the tumor can actually

1046
01:00:54.572 --> 01:00:58.052
induce fibroblasts to express a lot of galectin-1.

1047
01:00:58.712 --> 01:01:02.188
And-That's very interesting, at least because we know that the tumor

1048
01:01:02.248 --> 01:01:04.668
microenvironment will have a lot of galectin-1.

1049
01:01:05.688 --> 01:01:07.968
But in this case, we wanted to focus on the T cell

1050
01:01:08.908 --> 01:01:10.348
galectin-1, mainly because of

1051
01:01:11.268 --> 01:01:13.548
an intrinsic mechanism of exhaustion.

1052
01:01:13.568 --> 01:01:16.718
But it's very interesting to analyze what would happen across the different

1053
01:01:16.748 --> 01:01:18.028
populations as well.

1054
01:01:19.868 --> 01:01:22.428
Great talk. This is Robin Gusso from the MGH.

1055
01:01:23.368 --> 01:01:24.268
I noticed in your

1056
01:01:25.888 --> 01:01:29.748
mechanism section there, you were talking about galectin-1 binding checkpoints

1057
01:01:29.788 --> 01:01:33.128
like LAG-3 and VISTA and possibly DIGIT.

1058
01:01:34.648 --> 01:01:38.348
I missed, how did you arrive at those inhibitory receptors?

1059
01:01:39.828 --> 01:01:42.768
Which is basically we analyzed what receptors are

1060
01:01:43.728 --> 01:01:46.128
actually the ones that are targeted right now for therapy.

1061
01:01:46.188 --> 01:01:50.028
So like PD-1, CTLA-4, and I think lately LAG-3 are

1062
01:01:50.108 --> 01:01:54.008
actually being targeted. And basically, what other receptors are in

1063
01:01:54.048 --> 01:01:57.268
the way for being approved as possible targets.

1064
01:01:57.748 --> 01:01:57.888
Yeah.

1065
01:01:58.208 --> 01:02:00.188
So that's basically our line of thought.

1066
01:02:00.728 --> 01:02:04.388
Well, because one thing I think about is galectin-1 binds Glycnac, right?

1067
01:02:04.848 --> 01:02:05.048
Mm-hmm.

1068
01:02:05.428 --> 01:02:06.168
So there are

1069
01:02:07.128 --> 01:02:10.778
a number of ligands on T cells that are heavily glycosylated proteins

1070
01:02:11.148 --> 01:02:14.928
like CD2, CD7, and CD43.

1071
01:02:15.408 --> 01:02:19.108
And some of those, especially CD2, are important for T cell activation.

1072
01:02:19.168 --> 01:02:19.688
Yeah.

1073
01:02:19.748 --> 01:02:23.428
And have you guys considered that these are known galectin-1

1074
01:02:23.448 --> 01:02:27.088
ligands, and possibly interfering with their function or

1075
01:02:27.128 --> 01:02:28.288
cross-linking them in some way

1076
01:02:29.148 --> 01:02:31.468
could possibly inhibit T cell responses?

1077
01:02:31.788 --> 01:02:35.748
Do you know if it's dependent on cell intrinsic glycosylation?

1078
01:02:36.168 --> 01:02:40.088
You show lactose as a way to sort of block it, but you

1079
01:02:40.108 --> 01:02:42.998
could also strip the T cells of their-

1080
01:02:43.648 --> 01:02:43.658
Yeah

1081
01:02:43.658 --> 01:02:43.658
...

1082
01:02:44.628 --> 01:02:45.368
glycans.

1083
01:02:45.448 --> 01:02:45.958
Yeah, of course.

1084
01:02:47.068 --> 01:02:47.968
Basically, we focus on

1085
01:02:49.168 --> 01:02:52.588
co-inhibitory receptors because we know they have signaling pathways that will lead

1086
01:02:52.658 --> 01:02:56.568
to T cell exhaustion. But other members in our group are

1087
01:02:56.628 --> 01:02:56.858
also,

1088
01:02:57.868 --> 01:03:00.998
I wouldn't say they're focusing, but they study how galectin-1 binds to other

1089
01:03:01.288 --> 01:03:05.248
molecules in myeloid cells or T cells as well.

1090
01:03:05.308 --> 01:03:08.188
And it's not something we're not aware of.

1091
01:03:08.467 --> 01:03:12.088
I'm not focusing on that. And about your other comment,

1092
01:03:13.268 --> 01:03:14.828
yeah, it's very interesting because we know

1093
01:03:15.668 --> 01:03:19.537
it binds to different glycans, and in fact, these glycans are modified on the

1094
01:03:19.537 --> 01:03:22.578
tumor site. They're modified not only on tumor site, but on

1095
01:03:23.748 --> 01:03:27.648
the activation pathway. For example, as T cells are

1096
01:03:27.728 --> 01:03:30.998
activated versus the naive cell, they will start expressing more

1097
01:03:31.448 --> 01:03:34.948
galectin-1 permissive glycans, so the galectin-1 could bind more.

1098
01:03:35.868 --> 01:03:39.548
And of course, on tumor site, glycophenotype of the cells will be

1099
01:03:39.588 --> 01:03:41.828
different than that of in vitro cells, for example.

1100
01:03:42.118 --> 01:03:45.368
It's definitely something we are keeping in mind, and we actually have some

1101
01:03:45.388 --> 01:03:48.728
experiments. I can't tell you any results yet, but to

1102
01:03:49.848 --> 01:03:50.408
analyze that.

1103
01:03:50.888 --> 01:03:52.368
That's great. Thank you. Nice talk.

1104
01:03:52.388 --> 01:03:52.568
Thank you.

1105
01:03:54.428 --> 01:03:55.408
All right. Thank you very much.

1106
01:03:55.528 --> 01:03:55.908
Thank you.

1107
01:04:00.688 --> 01:04:04.528
Okay. Last talk of this session is Yaita Senat from

1108
01:04:04.888 --> 01:04:08.787
the Broad Institute of MIT and Harvard, and she's going to tell us about

1109
01:04:08.848 --> 01:04:12.708
her work understanding compensatory signaling

1110
01:04:12.768 --> 01:04:15.928
after PTPN 1 and 2 blockade.

1111
01:04:17.248 --> 01:04:20.068
Thank you, Megan, for the introduction, and the organizers for the opportunity to

1112
01:04:20.128 --> 01:04:23.688
present my work here. We've been hearing amazing talks about how we can

1113
01:04:23.728 --> 01:04:25.908
rewire T cell signaling and functionality.

1114
01:04:26.248 --> 01:04:29.328
And over the next 10 minutes, I'll share how we have addressed this question.

1115
01:04:29.368 --> 01:04:33.218
And to do this, we focus on a target that our lab has been deeply investigating for

1116
01:04:33.288 --> 01:04:36.208
some years now, which is the phosphatase PTPN2.

1117
01:04:36.988 --> 01:04:38.068
I have nothing to disclose.

1118
01:04:39.328 --> 01:04:42.828
PTPN2 is a protein tyrosine phosphatase that regulate a variety of cellular

1119
01:04:42.928 --> 01:04:46.768
processes by either dephosphorylating receptors or non-receptor protein

1120
01:04:46.788 --> 01:04:50.028
tyrosine kinases, which could include JAK and STAT proteins.

1121
01:04:50.688 --> 01:04:54.597
In T cells, PTPN2 is a critical checkpoint for cytokine and TCR signaling,

1122
01:04:54.968 --> 01:04:58.488
and inhibition or deletion of PTPN2 enhances T cell function,

1123
01:04:58.608 --> 01:05:01.948
increasing proliferation, effector function, and activation.

1124
01:05:03.068 --> 01:05:06.368
Some years ago, our lab described how either systemic inhibition of

1125
01:05:06.408 --> 01:05:10.388
PTPN2 with the cytactive inhibitor AC44 or PTPN2

1126
01:05:10.428 --> 01:05:14.288
knockout CAR T cells were able to effectively control tumors, in some

1127
01:05:14.308 --> 01:05:16.648
cases even better than anti-PD-1 treatment.

1128
01:05:17.177 --> 01:05:21.028
And this antitumor response was mediated by a unique population

1129
01:05:21.068 --> 01:05:24.568
of CD8 T cells that show enhanced memory and effector

1130
01:05:24.588 --> 01:05:26.268
phenotype and a reduced exhaustion.

1131
01:05:26.958 --> 01:05:30.728
And our analysis of these cells also show striking JAK-STAT

1132
01:05:30.788 --> 01:05:34.128
signaling pathways upregulated in these cells, including IL6,

1133
01:05:34.628 --> 01:05:36.248
JAK-STAT, or IL2, STAT5.

1134
01:05:37.148 --> 01:05:39.628
However, this data also highlights two main limitations.

1135
01:05:39.668 --> 01:05:43.588
The first one, that PTPN2 is not sufficient to induce curative responses.

1136
01:05:44.088 --> 01:05:47.628
And secondly, that the exact signaling mechanisms

1137
01:05:47.668 --> 01:05:51.348
happening in these enhanced effector T cells inhibited for

1138
01:05:51.368 --> 01:05:54.818
PTPN2 remains unclear. And so by mapping the signaling

1139
01:05:55.188 --> 01:05:58.588
pathways happening in these cells, we will be able to optimize

1140
01:05:58.708 --> 01:06:00.588
strategies to improve T cell function.

1141
01:06:02.288 --> 01:06:05.958
And so to address this question and to study the impact of

1142
01:06:05.988 --> 01:06:09.968
PTPN2 on exhaustion, we develop a chronic stimulation assay based on the

1143
01:06:09.988 --> 01:06:13.888
repetitive stimulation of T cells with anti-CD3/CD28 beads in

1144
01:06:13.908 --> 01:06:16.008
the presence of low concentration of IL-2.

1145
01:06:16.688 --> 01:06:18.628
We then characterize this cell by single cell.

1146
01:06:19.568 --> 01:06:23.528
And to characterize individual cytokine signaling pathways occurring in these cells

1147
01:06:23.588 --> 01:06:27.168
by single cell, we make use of the CytoSig analysis.

1148
01:06:27.668 --> 01:06:31.568
CytoSig is a curated database of known cytokine responses

1149
01:06:31.708 --> 01:06:34.368
and a predictive model developed by the Oguchida Finney lab.

1150
01:06:35.288 --> 01:06:38.348
And so by cross-referencing our transcriptomic data to these

1151
01:06:38.948 --> 01:06:42.348
established gene signatures, the model is capable of

1152
01:06:42.368 --> 01:06:45.708
predicting which cytokine networks are happening in our samples.

1153
01:06:46.168 --> 01:06:49.568
And we then cross-validate our findings by phosphoproteomics and flow

1154
01:06:49.608 --> 01:06:50.228
cytometry.

1155
01:06:51.428 --> 01:06:55.068
And so we perform this chronic stimulation assay either in the presence or absence

1156
01:06:55.128 --> 01:06:58.758
of this PTPN2 inhibitor, and then we collect the cells at the end of the assay and

1157
01:06:58.808 --> 01:07:02.788
perform single-cell RNA seq. And consistent with our previous

1158
01:07:02.948 --> 01:07:06.568
in vivo models-Pre-chronically stimulated T cells inhibited for

1159
01:07:06.608 --> 01:07:10.328
PTPN2 show enhanced memory gene signatures and also

1160
01:07:10.588 --> 01:07:12.388
depletion of terminal exhausted genes.

1161
01:07:12.828 --> 01:07:15.348
And this was also further validated by flow cytometry.

1162
01:07:15.488 --> 01:07:18.898
When we look at AC484 T cells, these cells express lower

1163
01:07:18.968 --> 01:07:22.788
PD-1, lower TIM-3, also lower TOX and CD39.

1164
01:07:24.448 --> 01:07:28.148
And so we next attempt to identify which were the key signaling events

1165
01:07:28.208 --> 01:07:31.628
happening in these cells. And as I mentioned, we used the CyTOsig analysis.

1166
01:07:31.968 --> 01:07:35.508
And I'm showing here chronic CD8s, but we observed the same results in CD4s.

1167
01:07:36.458 --> 01:07:39.768
And we observed that in these chronically stimulated T cells, there was a strong

1168
01:07:39.808 --> 01:07:43.708
upregulation of IL-10, STAT3 pathways, also IL-21,

1169
01:07:43.788 --> 01:07:47.488
STAT3, and STAT1 pathways. But at the same time, we observe a

1170
01:07:48.428 --> 01:07:51.268
downregulation of the IL-2/STAT5 pathway.

1171
01:07:52.088 --> 01:07:55.968
And this was most consistent with downregulation of canonical STAT5 effector

1172
01:07:56.028 --> 01:07:59.548
molecules and upregulation of STAT3 transcription factors.

1173
01:08:00.968 --> 01:08:04.488
And to further confirm that these findings were not

1174
01:08:04.498 --> 01:08:08.448
specific for the in vitro assay, we then performed the same analysis

1175
01:08:08.508 --> 01:08:12.388
on our previous published single-cell RNA-seq data of tumors treated

1176
01:08:12.428 --> 01:08:16.248
with AC484 drug. And when we look at these T cells from these tumors,

1177
01:08:16.628 --> 01:08:20.568
again, we observe that there was an upregulation of IL-10, STAT3, also

1178
01:08:20.648 --> 01:08:23.788
IL-6, STAT3 pathways, also interferon and STAT1 pathways.

1179
01:08:24.228 --> 01:08:26.927
But again, a downregulation of the IL-2/STAT pathway.

1180
01:08:28.968 --> 01:08:32.779
And we then cross-validate these findings by phosphoproteomics and

1181
01:08:32.808 --> 01:08:36.449
also by flow cytometry. So we perform again the chronic stimulation assay.

1182
01:08:36.608 --> 01:08:39.508
We collect the cells at the end of the assay and perform phosphoproteomics and also

1183
01:08:39.529 --> 01:08:41.369
characterize the assays by flow cytometry.

1184
01:08:42.608 --> 01:08:44.148
And we were able to

1185
01:08:45.148 --> 01:08:48.708
recover more than 50,000 phosphopeptides in our phosphoproteomic analysis, so this

1186
01:08:48.748 --> 01:08:50.288
was a very rich data set.

1187
01:08:51.108 --> 01:08:54.489
And similarly to the CyTOsig analysis, we observed a

1188
01:08:55.869 --> 01:08:59.428
decreased number of phosphopeptides for JAK proteins, especially JAK1,

1189
01:08:59.928 --> 01:09:03.388
and also for phosphopeptides of STAT5A and STAT5B.

1190
01:09:04.608 --> 01:09:08.248
And similarly to the single-cell RNA-seq, we do observe increased

1191
01:09:08.508 --> 01:09:11.728
number of phosphopeptides for STAT3 and STAT1.

1192
01:09:11.768 --> 01:09:15.268
And we then validate this by flow cytometry using specific phospho-site

1193
01:09:15.308 --> 01:09:17.768
antibodies for p-STAT3, STAT1, and STAT5.

1194
01:09:18.808 --> 01:09:22.568
As you can see here, STAT3 is one of the main pathways upregulated in these

1195
01:09:22.608 --> 01:09:26.588
cells, and we observe increased number of p-STAT3

1196
01:09:26.648 --> 01:09:30.529
levels in our PTPN2-inhibited T cells compared to the DMSO

1197
01:09:30.568 --> 01:09:34.489
group. And the magnitude of this increase is even greater as the cells become

1198
01:09:34.529 --> 01:09:37.329
more exhausted if we compare day

1199
01:09:38.449 --> 01:09:40.728
14 with day six.

1200
01:09:41.788 --> 01:09:43.648
And this was also true for p-STAT1.

1201
01:09:44.888 --> 01:09:48.489
But if we look at p-STAT5, even though PTPN2-inhibited T cells

1202
01:09:48.888 --> 01:09:52.449
show higher levels of p-STAT5 compared to the DMSO group, the

1203
01:09:52.588 --> 01:09:56.148
magnitude of this increase is significantly smaller if we

1204
01:09:56.768 --> 01:10:00.648
compare it to on day six when the cells are not yet fully

1205
01:10:00.668 --> 01:10:04.568
exhausted. And this is summarized here, where it highlights

1206
01:10:04.578 --> 01:10:08.418
that STAT3 and STAT1 pathways are the main pathways activated in these

1207
01:10:08.488 --> 01:10:12.058
chronically stimulated T cells. And so these were very

1208
01:10:12.108 --> 01:10:15.728
surprising finding for us since us and others have shown that

1209
01:10:16.068 --> 01:10:19.748
acutely stimulated T cells inhibited for PTPN2 show a

1210
01:10:19.868 --> 01:10:21.847
strong IL-2/STAT5 pathway as well.

1211
01:10:22.168 --> 01:10:25.048
This is indeed what we observe in acutely stimulated cells.

1212
01:10:25.668 --> 01:10:27.128
And so to nominate potential

1213
01:10:28.528 --> 01:10:32.468
mechanisms responsible for this downregulation of STAT5, we went back

1214
01:10:32.478 --> 01:10:36.348
to the single cell, and we look at genes induced by the STAT3 pathway

1215
01:10:36.428 --> 01:10:39.448
since this was one of the main pathways upregulated in these cells.

1216
01:10:40.288 --> 01:10:44.128
And so when we look at genes induced by STAT3 pathways that were

1217
01:10:44.248 --> 01:10:48.148
upregulated in our PTPN2-inhibited T cells, one of them was SOCS3.

1218
01:10:48.928 --> 01:10:52.628
And this was not only true in the in vitro exhaustion assay, but if we look again

1219
01:10:52.768 --> 01:10:56.348
on the TILs from tumors treated with the AC484 drug,

1220
01:10:56.728 --> 01:10:58.588
these cells also overexpress SOCS3.

1221
01:10:59.738 --> 01:11:02.508
And SOCS3 is a known inhibitor of JAK-STAT pathway.

1222
01:11:02.608 --> 01:11:06.408
It's usually induced by IL-10, IL-6, or IL-21/STAT3 pathways.

1223
01:11:06.828 --> 01:11:10.668
And when it's expressed, SOCS3 can bind directly the active site of

1224
01:11:10.708 --> 01:11:12.068
JAK proteins, and it

1225
01:11:12.908 --> 01:11:16.808
therefore stops further STAT5 phosphorylation, but it also marks

1226
01:11:16.848 --> 01:11:18.628
these JAK proteins for degradation.

1227
01:11:19.828 --> 01:11:23.668
And so we hypothesized that SOCS3 could be one of

1228
01:11:23.728 --> 01:11:23.967
the

1229
01:11:24.868 --> 01:11:26.448
potential candidates mediating this

1230
01:11:27.268 --> 01:11:29.748
downregulation of the IL-2/STAT5 pathway.

1231
01:11:29.788 --> 01:11:33.118
And to test this hypothesis, we generate knockout T cells for

1232
01:11:33.188 --> 01:11:36.808
PTPN2, SOCS3, or double knockout T cells for PTPN2 and

1233
01:11:36.868 --> 01:11:40.728
SOCS3. We then perform the chronic stimulation assay, and then we characterize the

1234
01:11:40.768 --> 01:11:44.628
cells at the end of this assay. The first thing that we notice is that

1235
01:11:44.668 --> 01:11:47.828
double knockout PTPN2 and SOCS3 show strong

1236
01:11:48.528 --> 01:11:51.128
levels of IL-2/STAT5 compared to the

1237
01:11:52.088 --> 01:11:52.808
single knockouts.

1238
01:11:53.728 --> 01:11:57.548
There was also a slight increase in p-STAT3, but this

1239
01:11:57.568 --> 01:12:01.088
